  "prompt": "What are the types of induction motors?",
  "response": "Induction motors are broadly classified into two main types based on the rotor design:\n\n**1. Squirrel-Cage Induction Motor:**\n\n*   **Description:** This is the most common type of induction motor due to its simple, robust construction and low cost. The rotor consists of a laminated steel core with embedded copper or aluminum bars short-circuited at both ends by end rings. These bars resemble a squirrel cage, hence the name.  No external electrical connections are needed for the rotor.\n\n*   **Advantages:**\n    *   Simple and robust construction\n    *   Low cost\n    *   High efficiency\n    *   Low maintenance\n    *   Relatively high starting torque (depending on design)\n    *   Good speed regulation\n\n*   **Disadvantages:**\n    *   Starting torque can be relatively low for some designs.\n    *   Difficult to control speed precisely without variable frequency drives (VFDs).\n    *   High inrush current during starting.\n    *   Power factor lags significantly at light loads.\n\n*   **Applications:**\n    *   Pumps\n    *   Fans\n    *   Blowers\n    *   Conveyors\n    *   Machine tools\n    *   General-purpose applications\n\n**2. Wound-Rotor (Slip-Ring) Induction Motor:**\n\n*   **Description:** The rotor has a three-phase, distributed winding similar to the stator winding. The ends of the rotor winding are connected to slip rings mounted on the rotor shaft.  Carbon brushes ride on these slip rings, allowing external resistors to be connected in series with the rotor circuit.\n\n*   **Advantages:**\n    *   High starting torque, which can be controlled by varying the external resistance.\n    *   Lower starting current compared to squirrel-cage motors.\n    *   Adjustable speed (to some extent), especially with external resistance.\n\n*   **Disadvantages:**\n    *   More complex and expensive than squirrel-cage motors.\n    *   Higher maintenance due to brushes and slip rings.\n    *   Lower efficiency than squirrel-cage motors (especially with external resistance).\n    *   Lower power factor at reduced speeds.\n\n*   **Applications:**\n    *   Cranes\n    *   Hoists\n    *   Elevators\n    *   Compressors\n    *   Applications requiring high starting torque and/or adjustable speed.\n\n**Beyond these two main types, there are variations and sub-categories based on specific design features and applications, including:**\n\n*   **Single-Phase Induction Motors:**  Designed to operate on single-phase power supplies.  These often use auxiliary windings and starting mechanisms like capacitors or shaded poles to initiate rotation. Common types include:\n    *   Split-Phase Motor\n    *   Capacitor-Start Motor\n    *   Capacitor-Run Motor\n    *   Permanent-Split Capacitor (PSC) Motor\n    *   Shaded-Pole Motor\n\n*   **Linear Induction Motors (LIM):** Instead of a rotating stator and rotor, these motors have a \"unrolled\" stator and rotor, producing linear motion directly. They are used in applications like high-speed trains, sliding doors, and industrial automation.\n\n*   **Synchronous Induction Motors:**  A hybrid type where the rotor is designed to lock into synchronism with the rotating magnetic field after starting as an induction motor.\n\n*   **Specialty Squirrel Cage Motors:** These are squirrel cage motors with specific designs to meet particular needs. Examples include:\n    *   **High-Slip Motors:** Designed to have high slip, resulting in higher starting torque and lower starting current, but lower efficiency and poor speed regulation.\n    *   **Double-Cage Motors:**  Have two sets of bars in the squirrel cage, each with different characteristics, to improve starting torque and efficiency.\n\nThe choice of induction motor type depends on the specific application requirements, including starting torque, speed control, efficiency, cost, and maintenance considerations. Squirrel-cage motors are generally preferred for their simplicity and reliability unless there is a specific need for the features offered by wound-rotor or other specialized motor types.\n",
